    "body": "> Brother, I already install node using nvm, why do I need to install node once again? I don't get it.\r\n\r\n@lawweiliang As you know, Node.js requires a build system because large parts of it â€” and its dependencies â€” are written in languages that require compilation. See [NodeJS dependency page.](https://nodejs.org/en/docs/meta/topics/dependencies/#dependencies)\r\n\r\nThe error messages in the original ticket description, log the necessary runtimes could not be found for node-gyp to work, and suggest installing the latest version of Visual Studio with Desktop development with C++. [NodeJS' Windows installation](https://nodejs.org/en/download/) installs this as part of its process, however, since you already have a node version manager installed, I recommend following [Microsoft's troubleshooting page](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/dev-environment/javascript/nodejs-on-windows#install-nvm-windows-nodejs-and-npm) to get your Node environment set up correctly.\r\n\r\nAlso, to help us better support Windows, which Node version Manager do you use? Is it Corey Butler's windows-nvm, volta, nvs, or another tool? Thanks in advance.\r\n",
